Fallon (2001, 2004) notes intervocalic [[lenition]], such as {{IPA|/b/}} → {{IPA|[β]}}; [[syncope (phonetics)|syncope]], as in the name of the language, {{IPA|/bɨlín/}} → {{IPA|[blín]}}; [[debuccalization]] with secondary articulation preserved, as in {{IPA|/dérekʷʼa}} → {{IPA|[dɛ́rɛʔʷa]}} 'mud for bricks'. Intriguingly, the ejectives have voiced allophones, which according to Fallon (2004) "provides an important empirical precedent" for one of the more criticized aspects of the [[glottalic theory]] of Indo-European. For example,

